|151|45|E|display=inline,title}}<ref name=mouth_topo>Topographic maps 9232 Newcastle, 92323N Beresfield</ref>\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|1|m|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = [[Hunter River (New South Wales)|Hunter River]] catchment\n| basin_size         = \n| tributaries_left   = [[Chichester River]], Carowiry Creek, Black Camp Creek\n| tributaries_right  = Myall Creek (New South Wales), Tabbil Creek, Wallarobba Creek, Unwarrabin Creek, Chambers Creek (New South Wales), Tumbledown Creek, Stony Creek (New South Wales)\n| custom_label       = [[National park]]\n| custom_data        = [[Barrington Tops National Park|Barrington Tops NP]]\n| bridges            = [[Williams River bridge, Clarence Town|Clarence Town bridge]]\n| extra              = <ref name=gnb>{{NSW GNR|id=SXYbWysyan|title=Williams River|date=24 July 1970|accessdate=3 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=bonzle>{{cite web|url=http://www.bonzle.com/c/a?a=p&p=213147&cmd=sp|title=Map of Williams River, NSW|work=Bonzle Digital Atlas of Australia|accessdate=3 March 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Williams River''' is a [[perennial stream]] that is a tributary of the [[Hunter River (New South Wales)|Hunter River]], in the [[Hunter Region]] of [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]].\n\n==Course and features==\nThe Williams River rises on the southern slopes of the [[Barrington Tops]] below Careys Peak within [[Barrington Tops National Park]], and flows generally southeast and south, joined by ten [[tributary|tributaries]] including [[Chichester River]], before reaching its [[confluence]] with the Hunter River at [[Raymond Terrace]]. The river descends {{convert|749|m}} over its {{convert|142|km}} [[watercourse|course]];<ref name=bonzle/> through [[Dungog, New South Wales|Dungog]], [[Clarence Town, New South Wales|Clarence Town]] and [[Seaham, New South Wales|Seaham]].\n\nAt Clarence Town, the Williams River is crossed by the [[Williams River bridge, Clarence Town|Clarence Town bridge]] that carries Limeburners Creek Road.<ref name=nswshr-1462>{{cite NSW SHR|5051362|Clarence Town Bridge over Williams River|hr=01462|fn=S91/01630|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|New South Wales}}\n* [[Grahamstown Dam]]\n* [[List of rivers of Australia]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nRaymond Terrace twin rivers.jpg|Confluence of the [[Hunter River (New South Wales)|Hunter]] and Williams rivers.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/ieo/Hunter/maplg.htm|title=Hunter River catchment|format=map|work=Office of Environment and Heritage|publisher=[[Government of New South Wales]]|date=}}\n\n{{Rivers of the Hunter-Central Rivers catchment |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Rivers of New South Wales |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Mid North Coast NSW |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Hunter Region places and items of interest}}\n{{Suburbs of Port Stephens}}\n{{Suburbs of Dungog Shire}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Dungog Shire]]\n[[Category:Port Stephens Council]]\n[[Category:Rivers of the Hunter Region]]\n[[Category:Mid North Coast]]\n[[Category:Hunter River]]\n\n\n{{NewSouthWales-river-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rangasyd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:+stack", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Williams_River_(New_South_Wales)"}
{"title_page": "Yong Mei", "text_new": "{{infobox person\n| name = Yong Mei\n| image =Yong Mei-2197.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Yong Mei at the [[69th Berlin International Film Festival]]\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|02|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Hohhot]], [[China]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of International Business and Economics (Beijing)|University of International Business and Economics]]\n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 1997\u2013present\n| agent =\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| awards = {{awards|award=[[69th Berlin International Film Festival]]|name=[[Silver Bear for Best Actress]]}}\n| module = {{Infobox Chinese\n |child=yes\n |c=\u548f\u6885\n |p = Y\u01d2ng M\u00e9i\n }}\n}}\n\n'''Yong Mei''' ({{zh|c=\u548f\u6885}}; born 14 February 1970) is a Chinese actress. In 2019, she won the [[Silver Bear for Best Actress]] at the [[69th Berlin International Film Festival]] for her performance in the film ''[[So Long, My Son]]'' directed by [[Wang Xiaoshuai]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAn ethnic [[Mongols in China|Mongol]], Yong Mei was born on 14 February 1970 in [[Hohhot]], the capital of China's [[Inner Mongolia|Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmgcb.com.cn/yule/2019/0218/191881.html|title=\u8499\u53e4\u65cf\u6f14\u5458\u548f\u6885 \u64d2\u201c\u94f6\u718a\u201d|last=Hai Qing \u6d77\u6e05|date=2019-02-18|website=Inner Mongolia Morning News|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> Her original name in Mongolian is '''Sunjidma''' ({{lang-mn|{{MongolUnicode|\u1830\u1826\u1828\u1835\u1822\u1833\u182e\u202f\u1820}}|script=Mong}}, {{lang-mn|\u0421\u04af\u043d\u0436\u0438\u0434\u043c\u0430\u0430|script=Cyrl|translit=S\u00fcn\u017eidmaa|translit-std=ISO|label=none}}, {{IPA-mn|sunt\u0283itma\u02d0}}, {{zh|s=\u68ee\u5409\u5fb7\u739b|p=S\u0113nj\u00edd\u00e9m\u01ce}}), meaning \"fairy\", which has given rise to her nickname \"Sister Fairy\" ({{Lang-zh|s=\u4ed9\u59d0\u513f|p=xi\u0101nji\u011br}}).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/ent/2019-03/22/c_1124267382.htm|title=\u548f\u6885 \u6211\u7684\u751f\u6d3b\u6bd4\u5267\u672c\u7cbe\u5f69\u591a\u4e86|date=2019-03-22|website=Xinhua|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> She studied business administration at the [[University of International Business and Economics (Beijing)|University of International Business and Economics]] in [[Beijing]],<ref name=\":0\" /> where she was active in performing arts.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduation from university, she initially worked in foreign trade, and later in the studio of the influential television hostess [[Xu Gehui]] (\u8bb8\u6208\u8f89).<ref name=\":3\" /> On the recommendation of Xu, Yong Mei starred in the 1997 [[television drama]] ''The Man Who Herds the Clouds'' (\u7267\u4e91\u7684\u7537\u4eba) and began her acting career.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://cul.china.com.cn/renwu/2012-02/02/content_4785689.htm|title=\u548f\u6885\uff1a\u6211\u4e0d\u662f\u4e2a\u6709\u91ce\u5fc3\u7684\u6f14\u5458|last=Cao Songbo \u66f9\u5d69\u535a|date=2012-02-02|website=Culture China|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> She had her breakout role in the 2004 television drama ''A Chinese-style Divorce'' (\u4e2d\u56fd\u5f0f\u79bb\u5a5a), which made her wildly popular.<ref name=\":0\" /> She was also praised for her performances in the TV series ''Cell Phone'' (\u624b\u673a), ''Ocean Paradise'' (\u6d77\u6d0b\u5929\u5802), ''You Are My Lover'' (\u4f60\u662f\u6211\u7231\u4eba), and ''Cliff'' (\u60ac\u5d16, 2012).<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2015, Yong Mei appeared in [[Hou Hsiao-hsien]]'s film [[The Assassin (2015 film)|''The Assassin'']] (or ''Assassin Nie Yinniang''), in which she plays the mother of the title character, Nie Yinniang. The production lasted from 2012 to 2014; she thoroughly enjoyed the experience and held the film in high regard. She did not accept a major role for the next few years for lack of a suitable script that met her standard for quality.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe next major film she appeared in was ''[[So Long, My Son]]'', directed by [[Wang Xiaoshuai]], in which she portrays a mother who has lost her only son.<ref name=\":0\" /> To prepare for the role, she interviewed a real-life mother who had lost her only child. She originally scheduled two hours for the interview, but it was eventually extended to seven hours and gave her deep insight into a mother's sorrow.<ref name=\":0\" /> The film premiered at the [[69th Berlin International Film Festival]] on 14 February 2019,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201902/18/WS5c6a09c1a3106c65c34e9ccf.html|title=Chinese actors win top awards at Berlin festival|last=Chen|first=Meiling|date=2019-02-18|work=China Daily|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/europe/article/2186490/lead-roles-chinese-saga-so-long-my-son-share-best-actor-awards|title=Lead roles in Chinese saga \u2018So Long My Son\u2019 share best actor awards|date=2019-02-17|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> Yong Mei's 49th birthday.<ref name=\":0\" /> For their performance, Yong Mei and [[Wang Jingchun]], who plays her husband in the film, were awarded the [[Silver Bear for Best Actress]] and [[Silver Bear for Best Actor|Best Actor]], respectively.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/berlin-film-festival-2019-award-winners-1203141753/|title=Berlin Film Festival 2019: Nadav Lapid\u2019s \u2018Synonyms\u2019 Wins Golden Bear|last=Meza|first=Ed|date=2019-02-16|website=Variety|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> She was the first actress from mainland China to win the award.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nYong Mei is married to Luan Shu, the former lead singer of the Beijing rock band [[Black Panther (band)|Black Panther]]. She became a fan of the band after being introduced to its music by a friend, and starred in the music video for its song \"Don't Break My Heart\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=3619308|name=Yong Mei}}\n*[https://movie.douban.com/celebrity/1276041/ Yong Mei] on [[Douban]] {{in lang|zh}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Yong Mei\n|list =\n{{Golden Rooster Award Best Actress}}\n{{Silver Bear for Best Actress}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|China|Film}}\n\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Chinese actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Inner Mongolia]]\n[[Category:Chinese people of Mongolian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Hohhot]]\n[[Category:Beijing University of International Business and Economics alumni]]\n[[Category:Silver Bear for Best Actress winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox person\n| name = Yong Mei\n| image =Yong Mei-2197.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Yong Mei at the [[69th Berlin International Film Festival]]\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|02|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Hohhot]], [[China]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of International Business and Economics (Beijing)|University of International Business and Economics]]\n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 1997\u2013present\n| agent =\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| awards = {{awards|award=[[69th Berlin International Film Festival]]|name=[[Silver Bear for Best Actress]]}}\n| module = {{Infobox Chinese\n |child=yes\n |c=\u548f\u6885\n |p = Y\u01d2ng M\u00e9i\n }}\n}}\n\n'''Yong Mei''' ({{zh|c=\u548f\u6885}}; born 14 February 1970) is a Chinese actress. In 2019, she won the [[Silver Bear for Best Actress]] at the [[69th Berlin International Film Festival]] for her performance in the film ''[[So Long, My Son]]'' directed by [[Wang Xiaoshuai]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAn ethnic [[Mongols in China|Mongol]], Yong Mei was born on 14 February 1970 in [[Hohhot]], the capital of China's [[Inner Mongolia|Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmgcb.com.cn/yule/2019/0218/191881.html|title=\u8499\u53e4\u65cf\u6f14\u5458\u548f\u6885 \u64d2\u201c\u94f6\u718a\u201d|last=Hai Qing \u6d77\u6e05|date=2019-02-18|website=Inner Mongolia Morning News|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> Her original name in Mongolian is '''Sunjidma''' ({{lang-mn|{{MongolUnicode|\u1830\u1826\u1828\u1835\u1822\u1833\u182e\u202f\u1820}}|script=Mong}}, {{lang-mn|\u0421\u04af\u043d\u0436\u0438\u0434\u043c\u0430\u0430|script=Cyrl|translit=S\u00fcn\u017eidmaa|translit-std=ISO|label=none}}, {{IPA-mn|sunt\u0283itma\u02d0}}, {{zh|s=\u68ee\u5409\u5fb7\u739b|p=S\u0113nj\u00edd\u00e9m\u01ce}}), meaning \"fairy\", which has given rise to her nickname \"Sister Fairy\" ({{Lang-zh|s=\u4ed9\u59d0\u513f|p=xi\u0101nji\u011br}}).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/ent/2019-03/22/c_1124267382.htm|title=\u548f\u6885 \u6211\u7684\u751f\u6d3b\u6bd4\u5267\u672c\u7cbe\u5f69\u591a\u4e86|date=2019-03-22|website=Xinhua|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> She studied business administration at the [[University of International Business and Economics (Beijing)|University of International Business and Economics]] in [[Beijing]],<ref name=\":0\" /> where she was active in performing arts.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduation from university, she initially worked in foreign trade, and later in the studio of the influential television hostess [[Xu Gehui]] (\u8bb8\u6208\u8f89).<ref name=\":3\" /> On the recommendation of Xu, Yong Mei starred in the 1997 [[television drama]] ''The Man Who Herds the Clouds'' (\u7267\u4e91\u7684\u7537\u4eba) and began her acting career.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://cul.china.com.cn/renwu/2012-02/02/content_4785689.htm|title=\u548f\u6885\uff1a\u6211\u4e0d\u662f\u4e2a\u6709\u91ce\u5fc3\u7684\u6f14\u5458|last=Cao Songbo \u66f9\u5d69\u535a|date=2012-02-02|website=Culture China|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> She had her breakout role in the 2004 television drama ''A Chinese-style Divorce'' (\u4e2d\u56fd\u5f0f\u79bb\u5a5a), which made her wildly popular.<ref name=\":0\" /> She was also praised for her performances in the TV series ''Cell Phone'' (\u624b\u673a), ''Ocean Paradise'' (\u6d77\u6d0b\u5929\u5802), ''You Are My Lover'' (\u4f60\u662f\u6211\u7231\u4eba), and ''Cliff'' (\u60ac\u5d16, 2012).<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2015, Yong Mei appeared in [[Hou Hsiao-hsien]]'s film [[The Assassin (2015 film)|''The Assassin'']] (or ''Assassin Nie Yinniang''), in which she plays the mother of the title character, Nie Yinniang. The production lasted from 2012 to 2014; she thoroughly enjoyed the experience and held the film in high regard. She did not accept a major role for the next few years for lack of a suitable script that met her standard for quality.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe next major film she appeared in was ''[[So Long, My Son]]'', directed by [[Wang Xiaoshuai]], in which she portrays a mother who has lost her only son.<ref name=\":0\" /> To prepare for the role, she interviewed a real-life mother who had lost her only child. She originally scheduled two hours for the interview, but it was eventually extended to seven hours and gave her deep insight into a mother's sorrow.<ref name=\":0\" /> The film premiered at the [[69th Berlin International Film Festival]] on 14 February 2019,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201902/18/WS5c6a09c1a3106c65c34e9ccf.html|title=Chinese actors win top awards at Berlin festival|last=Chen|first=Meiling|date=2019-02-18|work=China Daily|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/europe/article/2186490/lead-roles-chinese-saga-so-long-my-son-share-best-actor-awards|title=Lead roles in Chinese saga \u2018So Long My Son\u2019 share best actor awards|date=2019-02-17|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> Yong Mei's 49th birthday.<ref name=\":0\" /> For their performance, Yong Mei and [[Wang Jingchun]], who plays her husband in the film, were awarded the [[Silver Bear for Best Actress]] and [[Silver Bear for Best Actor|Best Actor]], respectively.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/berlin-film-festival-2019-award-winners-1203141753/|title=Berlin Film Festival 2019: Nadav Lapid\u2019s \u2018Synonyms\u2019 Wins Golden Bear|last=Meza|first=Ed|date=2019-02-16|website=Variety|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> She was the first actress from mainland China to win the award.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nYong Mei is married to Luan Shu, the former lead singer of the Beijing rock band [[Black Panther (band)|Black Panther]]. She became a fan of the band after being introduced to its music by a friend, and starred in the music video for its song \"Don't Break My Heart\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=3619308|name=Yong Mei}}\n*[https://movie.douban.com/celebrity/1276041/ Yong Mei] on [[Douban]] {{in lang|zh}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Yong Mei\n|list =\n{{Golden Rooster Award Best Actress}}\n{{Silver Bear for Best Actress}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|China|Film}}\n\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Inner Mongolia]]\n[[Category:People from Hohhot]]\n[[Category:Beijing University of International Business and Economics alumni]]\n[[Category:Chinese people of Mongolian descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century Chinese actresses]]\n[[Category:Silver Bear for Best Actress winners]]\n", "name_user": "Diopic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:more accurate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yong_Mei"}
{"title_page": "Louis Sparre", "text_new": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Pehr Louis Sparre\n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Pehr Louis Sparre af S\u00f6fdeborg\n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = Swedish\n| residence      = \n| birth_date      = {{birth date|1863|8|3|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[Gravellona Lomellina]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date      = {{death date and age|1964|10|26|1863|8|3|df=yes}}\n| death_place     = [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| image = Pehr Louis Sparre - from Svenskt Portr\u00e4ttgalleri XX.png\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| website        = \n| country        = \n| sport          = [[Fencing]]\n| event          = \n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = \n| team           = \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = \n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''Pehr Louis Sparre af S\u00f6fdeborg''' (3 August 1863 &ndash; 26 October 1964) was a [[Sweden|Swedish]] painter, designer and draughtsman, most noted for his early work in the [[Finland|Finnish]] [[national romanticism]] and [[jugend]] styles. He also competed in the individual and team [[\u00e9p\u00e9e]] fencing events at the [[1912 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=   https://rkd.nl/en/explore/artists/74147|title= Pehr Louis  Sparre af S\u00f6fdeborg|publisher= RKD \u2013 Netherlands Institute for Art History|accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/sp/louis-count-sparre-1.html |title=Pehr Louis Sparre Olympic Results |accessdate=2010-04-17 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n<ref name=sbl>{{cite web|url= https://sok.riksarkivet.se/Sbl/Presentation.aspx?id=6214|title=  P Louis Sparre|publisher=   Svenskt biografiskt lexikon|author=   Tomas Bj\u00f6rk  |accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Gravellona Lomellina]], [[Italy]]. He was the son of  Pehr Ambj\u00f6rn Sparre af S\u00f6fdeborg (1828\u20131921) and Teresita Ad\u00e8le Josefa Gaetana Barbavara (1844\u20131867). His father had served as head of the banknote printing company for the [[Sveriges Riksbank]]. He spent his early childhood with the mother at Villa Teresita in Gravellona  while his father was often on business trips. After having suffered an accident, her mother died when he was four years old. He then moved with his father in [[Paris]] prior to being sent to Sweden for school studies. He attended the [[Royal Swedish Academy of Fine Arts]] before relocating to Paris.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://sok.riksarkivet.se/sbl/Presentation.aspx?id=6161|title=  P Ambj\u00f6rn Sparre|publisher=   Svenskt biografiskt lexikon|author=   Bj\u00f6rn Sylwan|accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSparre was a student at [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] in [[Paris]] from 1887 until 1890. He studied with [[Akseli Gallen-Kallela]], [[Eero J\u00e4rnefelt]] and [[Emil Wikstr\u00f6m]] and took part in painting trips in [[Karelia]] with Kallela and Wikstr\u00f6m. Sparre is often mentioned as a founder of the [[Karelianism]] movement, along with [[Akseli Gallen-Kallela]]. He moved to Finland in 1889, living there for almost two decades. In 1893, Sparre married Eva Mannerheim (1870\u20131958), an artist and the sister of [[Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim]].<ref name=\"sbl\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=  http://neba.finlit.fi/kalevala/index.php?m=203&s=205&l=3|title=  Karelianism och nationalromantik|publisher=Finnish Literary  Society   \n|accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1891, two of his works were exhibited at the [[Paris Salon]]. After the mid-1890s, Sparre reduced his work as a painter and instead worked on developing the industrial art and graphics industry in Finland. In 1897, he founded the Iris furniture and ceramics factory in [[Porvoo]]. Impressed by the pottery of the [[England|English]]-[[Belgium|Belgian]] ceramist and painter [[Alfred William Finch]], Sparre invited him to manage the ceramics department. By the request of his friend, [[Karl Emil St\u00e5hlberg]], Sparre also worked as the director for the first Finnish [[fictional film]], the 20-minute-long ''[[Salaviinanpolttajat]]'' in 1907.<ref name=\"sbl\"/>\n\nIn 1908, Sparre moved back to Sweden and continued his painting career, concentrating on [[portrait painting|portraiture]] and painting landscapes. By the time of his death in 1964 in [[Stockholm]], aged 101, Sparre had completed over 500 portraits.<ref name=\"sbl\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060507171926/http://www.amosanderson.fi/english/sparre.html Louis Sparre biography at the Amos Anderson art museum]\n*{{IMDb name|name=Louis Sparre|id=0817086}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sparre, Louis}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1964 deaths]]\n[[Category:Swedish centenarians]]\n[[Category:Swedish nobility]]\n[[Category:19th-century Swedish painters]]\n[[Category:Swedish male painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Swedish painters]]\n[[Category:Swedish male fencers]]\n[[Category:Swedish \u00e9p\u00e9e fencers]]\n[[Category:Olympic fencers of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Fencers at the 1912 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriates in Finland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Pehr Louis Sparre\n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Pehr Louis Sparre af S\u00f6fdeborg\n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = Swedish\n| residence      = \n| birth_date      = {{birth date|1863|8|3|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[Gravellona Lomellina]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date      = {{death date and age|1964|10|26|1863|8|3|df=yes}}\n| death_place     = [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| image = Pehr Louis Sparre - from Svenskt Portr\u00e4ttgalleri XX.png\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| website        = \n| country        = \n| sport          = [[Fencing]]\n| event          = \n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = \n| team           = \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = \n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''Pehr Louis Sparre af S\u00f6fdeborg''' (3 August 1863 &ndash; 26 October 1964) was a [[Sweden|Swedish]] painter, designer and draughtsman, most noted for his early work in the [[Finland|Finnish]] [[national romanticism]] and [[jugend]] styles. He also competed in the individual and team [[\u00e9p\u00e9e]] fencing events at the [[1912 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=   https://rkd.nl/en/explore/artists/74147|title= Pehr Louis  Sparre af S\u00f6fdeborg|publisher= RKD \u2013 Netherlands Institute for Art History|accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/sp/louis-count-sparre-1.html |title=Pehr Louis Sparre Olympic Results |accessdate=2010-04-17 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n<ref name=sbl>{{cite web|url= https://sok.riksarkivet.se/Sbl/Presentation.aspx?id=6214|title=  P Louis Sparre|publisher=   Svenskt biografiskt lexikon|author=   Tomas Bj\u00f6rk  |accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Gravellona Lomellina]], [[Italy]]. He was the son of  Pehr Ambj\u00f6rn Sparre af S\u00f6fdeborg (1828-1921) and Teresita Ad\u00e8le Josefa Gaetana Barbavara (1844-1867). His father had served as head of the banknote printing company for the [[Sveriges Riksbank]]. He spent his early childhood with the mother at Villa Teresita in Gravellona  while his father was often on business trips. After having suffered an accident, her mother died when he was four years old. He then moved with his father in [[Paris]] prior to being sent to Sweden for school studies. He attended the [[Royal Swedish Academy of Fine Arts]] prior to re-locating to Paris. <ref>{{cite web|url= https://sok.riksarkivet.se/sbl/Presentation.aspx?id=6161|title=  P Ambj\u00f6rn Sparre|publisher=   Svenskt biografiskt lexikon|author=   Bj\u00f6rn Sylwan|accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSparre was a student at [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] in [[Paris]] from  1887\u20131890. He studied with [[Akseli Gallen-Kallela]], [[Eero J\u00e4rnefelt]] and [[Emil Wikstr\u00f6m]] and took part in painting trips in [[Karelia]] with Kallela and Wikstr\u00f6m. Sparre is often mentioned as a founder of the [[Karelianism]] movement, along with [[Akseli Gallen-Kallela]]. He moved to Finland in 1889, living there for almost two decades. In 1893, Sparre married Eva Mannerheim (1870-1958), an artist and the sister of [[Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim]].<ref name=\"sbl\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=  http://neba.finlit.fi/kalevala/index.php?m=203&s=205&l=3|title=  Karelianism och nationalromantik|publisher=Finnish Literary  Society   \n|accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1891, two of his works were exhibited at the [[Paris Salon]]. After the mid-1890s, Sparre reduced his work as a painter and instead worked on developing the industrial art and graphics industry in Finland. In 1897, he founded the Iris furniture and ceramics factory in [[Porvoo]]. Impressed by the pottery of the [[England|English]]-[[Belgium|Belgian]] ceramist and painter [[Alfred William Finch]], Sparre invited him to manage the ceramics department. By the request of his friend, [[Karl Emil St\u00e5hlberg]], Sparre also worked as the director for the first Finnish [[fictional film]], the 20-minute-long ''[[Salaviinanpolttajat]]'' in 1907.<ref name=\"sbl\"/>\n\nIn 1908, Sparre moved back to Sweden and continued his painting career, concentrating on [[portrait painting|portraiture]] and painting landscapes. By the time of his death in 1964 in [[Stockholm]], aged 101, Sparre had completed over 500 portraits.<ref name=\"sbl\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060507171926/http://www.amosanderson.fi/english/sparre.html Louis Sparre biography at the Amos Anderson art museum]\n*{{IMDb name|name=Louis Sparre|id=0817086}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sparre, Louis}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1964 deaths]]\n[[Category:Swedish centenarians]]\n[[Category:Swedish nobility]]\n[[Category:19th-century Swedish painters]]\n[[Category:Swedish male painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Swedish painters]]\n[[Category:Swedish male fencers]]\n[[Category:Swedish \u00e9p\u00e9e fencers]]\n[[Category:Olympic fencers of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Fencers at the 1912 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriates in Finland]]\n", "name_user": "Ewulp", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louis_Sparre"}
{"title_page": "Rialto Towers", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name               = Rialto\n| image              = Rialto Towers in May 2017, edit.png \n| image_size         = 200px\n| caption            = Rialto as viewed from the base of the towers, in May 2017\n| highest_region     = [[List of tallest buildings in Melbourne|Melbourne]]\n| highest_start      = 1986\n| highest_end        = 1991\n| highest_prev       = [[Collins Place|Sofitel Hotel at Collins Place]]\n| highest_next       = [[101 Collins Street]]\n| location           = [[Melbourne, Australia]]\n| coordinates        = {{coord|37|49|08|S|144|57|30|E|region:AU|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date         = 1982\n| completion_date    = 1986\n| building_type      = Office\n| observatory        = {{convert|234|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=Emporis />\n| roof               = {{convert|251|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=Emporis>[http://www.emporis.com/building/rialtotowers-melbourne-australia Emporis \u2013 Rialto Towers]</ref>\n| architectural      = {{convert|251|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=Emporis />\n| antenna_spire      = {{convert|270|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| floor_count        = 55 (plus 3 underground)\n| floor_area         = {{convert|84000|m2|sqft|-2|abbr=on}}\n| architect          = [[Gerard de Preu and Partners]]<br />[[Perrott Lyon Mathieson]]\n| main_contractor    = [[Grocon|Grollo Australia]]\n}}\n\n'''Rialto''' (often '''The Rialto, or Rialto Towers''') is a [[skyscraper]] located at 525 [[Collins Street, Melbourne|Collins Street]], in the western side of the [[Melbourne central business district|central business district]] of [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]]. It was the tallest [[office]] building in the [[Southern Hemisphere]] when it was constructed.\n\nThe Rialto featured Melbourne's first skyscraper public observation deck which operated between 1994 and 31 December 2009.<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/video/2009/10/23/2722902.htm</ref> It was also the location of Melbourne's first [[Tower running]] event.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Robbs building melbourne.jpg|thumb|left|Robbs Building, demolished in 1980 to make way for the Rialto's concrete and glass podium]]\n[[File:Rialto old.....jpg|thumb|150px|right|The old Rialto Building was retained as part of the development.]]\nThe site of Rialto (Flinders Lane, Collins Street, Winfield Square and Robbs Lane) was occupied by several buildings including numerous small warehouses on Flinders Lane, Robb's Buildings (now demolished, named for the owner, railway builder [[John Robb (civil engineer)|John Robb]]), a grand classical styled 5-storey Victorian office building designed by Thomas Watts and Sons<ref>[http://www.slv.vic.gov.au/miscpics/0/0/9/doc/mp009620.shtml Robb's buildings, corner of Collins and King Streets Melbourne [picture&#93; by<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> in 1885, and one of the largest in the city at the time<ref>[http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A060044b.htm Robb, John (1834\u20131896) Biographical Entry \u2013 Australian Dictionary of Biography Online<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> two other interwar buildings on Collins Street, the Rialto Building (1889) designed by [[William Pitt (architect)|William Pitt]] and the Winfield Building (1890) designed by Charles Debro & Richard Speight, all part of an historic streetscape along Collins Street running up to the Olderfleet Building to the east.\n\nDuring the 1970s, the large derelict site was owned by the [[National Mutual Life Association of Australasia]] and it was around 1979 when the first development proposal was prepared and submitted to the [[Melbourne City Council]].\n\nLittle progress was made until 1980 when the site was acquired by [[Grocon|Grollo Australia]] in a joint venture with St Martin's Properties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rialto.com.au/|title=Building Construction|accessdate=17 January 2007|pages=(Building Profile \u2192 Features \u2192 Construction)}} <!-- due to Javascript navigation used at the site, it is impossible to provide a direct link to the source page --></ref> Though a campaign was run by the National Trust of Victoria against the demolition of Robb's Building, Grocon successfully argued that it stood in the way of its major twin-tower proposal. During the application process the Rialto and Windfield buildings were added to the Victorian Heritage Register, and a different future was determined for them. This involved the creation of a hotel utilising the whole of the long rear wing of the Rialto Building, the replacement of the rear wing of the Winfield Building, and the creation of an atrium between.\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Rialto Towers at night.jpg|thumb|left|Rialto at night.]]\nRobb's buildings were subsequently demolished opening the way for construction to begin on the Rialto.\n\nDesigned by architects Gerard de Preu and Partners in association with [[Perrott Lyon Mathieson]], the building was built between 1982 and 1986, opening in October 1986, and takes its name from the much older Rialto Building next door. The massive glass [[curtain wall (architecture)|curtain wall]] [[fa\u00e7ade]] of reinforced blue tinted mirrored glass is its central feature and changes colour during the day, ranging from a trademark dark blue to a brilliant gold during sunset.\n\nIt is {{convert|251|m|abbr=on}} high, with 55 floors<ref>http://www.rialto.com.au/#block-gp-global-leasing</ref> and 3 basement floors. It comprises two conjoined towers, the shorter North Tower being {{convert|185|m|abbr=on}} high with 43 floors. In total, there are {{convert|84000|m2|abbr=on}} of office space.\n\nEarly tenants moved into the lower floors while the upper floors were still under construction in 1984.\n\n==Rialto Run-up==\nInspired by the popular [[Empire State Building Run-Up]], a stair race up the {{convert|242|m|abbr=on}}, 1222\u20131254 step race to the 53rd floor of the Rialto building was first run in the late 1980s and became an annual event with both men's and women's divisions known as the '''Rialto Run-up'''.  Previous winners include Robin Rishworth (1989,1990); Geoff Case (1991).  The winner was awarded with a trip to [[New York City]] to compete in the Empire State Building race. The event was run until 2005 and competitors had to go up 1254 steps.<ref>Cool Running website [http://www.coolrunning.com.au/mediareleases/2005/rialto.pdf Rialto Run-Up 2005 Run 1254 stairs to the top! ] Retrieved 8 April 2015</ref>\n\n==Observation Deck==\nThe Melbourne Observation Deck opened to the public on 19 July 1994 and was located on the 55th floor of the South Tower, at {{convert|234|m|abbr=on}}. Views of up to {{convert|60|km|abbr=on}} can be had on a clear day. The floor is serviced by two passenger [[Elevator|lift]]s. On 31 December 2009, the observation deck closed. In 2010, the fine dining restaurant, Vue de monde, and associated cocktail bar, Lui Bar, opened for trade on Level 55.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/travel/travel-news/end-in-view-for-rialtos-top-deck-20091007-gn8m.html|title=End in view for Rialto's top deck|last=Dobbin|first=Marika|date=8 October 2009|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=21 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rialto view night.jpg|800px|center|thumb|Panoramic view from the Rialto at night showing the [[Melbourne city centre]] and [[Southbank, Victoria|Southbank]] illuminated]]\n[[File:Melbourne Skyline from Rialto Crop - Nov 2008.jpg|800px|thumb|center|A ~180-degree panoramic image of Melbourne's [[Hoddle Grid]] ([[Melbourne city centre|CBD]]) and [[Southbank, Victoria|Southbank]] on the right side, as viewed from the Rialto Observation Deck]]\n\n{{Clear left}}\n\n==Statistics==\n[[File:Melbourne at night, 2014.jpg|thumb|Rialto dominating Melbourne's western skyline]]\nRialto consists of two interconnected towers, North and South, with rooftop floors at Level 41 and Level 58 respectively. There are 36 passenger lifts, {{convert|95|km|abbr=on}} of lift cables, 706 lift door openings and 1,450 staircase steps.  The outer surface of the building has 13,000 windows. There are five basement levels of car park available for occupiers and casual users. When completed in 1986, The Rialto surpassed Sydney's [[MLC Centre]] to become Australia's tallest building at {{convert|251|m|abbr=on}}. It was the tallest for five years until being surpassed by [[101 Collins Street]] in 1991. It is currently the [[List of tallest buildings in Australia|tenth tallest building in Australia]].\n\n{{Tallest buildings in Australia|taller=[[Bourke Place]]|theight={{convert|254|m}}|shorter=[[Infinity Tower (Brisbane)|Infinity Tower]]|sheight={{convert|249|m}}}}\n\n{{Melbourne tall buildings|taller=[[Bourke Place]]|theight={{convert|254|m}}|shorter=[[Melbourne Central Shopping Centre|Melbourne Central]]|sheight={{convert|246|m}}}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Rialto Tower August 2007.JPG|August 2007\nFile:Rialto Towers in Aug. 2015 (cropped).jpg|August 2015\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Architecture}}}}\n* [[Architecture of Melbourne]]\n* [[Australian landmarks]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Melbourne]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.rialto.com.au/ Rialto Towers]\n*[http://www.melbourne360rialto.com.au/ Melbourne Observation Deck]\n*[http://www.walkingmelbourne.com/building280.html Walking Melbourne profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060526194812/http://www.supersprint.com.au/Default.aspx?Menu=269&Content=2839&Template=1 Rialto Run Up]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110218133217/http://www.grollogroup.com.au/grollo-property/development/rialto/ Grollo Group built & owns the Rialto Towers]\n\n{{Melbourne Skyscrapers}}\n{{Melbourne landmarks}}\n\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1986]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Office buildings in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Australia]]\n[[Category:Collins Street, Melbourne]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name               = Rialto\n| image              = Rialto Towers in May 2017, edit.png \n| image_size         = 200px\n| caption            = Rialto as viewed from the base of the towers, in May 2017\n| highest_region     = [[List of tallest buildings in Melbourne|Melbourne]]\n| highest_start      = 1986\n| highest_end        = 1991\n| highest_prev       = [[Collins Place|Sofitel Hotel at Collins Place]]\n| highest_next       = [[101 Collins Street]]\n| location           = [[Melbourne, Australia]]\n| coordinates        = {{coord|37|49|08|S|144|57|30|E|region:AU|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date         = 1982\n| completion_date    = 1986\n| building_type      = Office\n| observatory        = {{convert|234|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=Emporis />\n| roof               = {{convert|251|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=Emporis>[http://www.emporis.com/building/rialtotowers-melbourne-australia Emporis \u2013 Rialto Towers]</ref>\n| architectural      = {{convert|251|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=Emporis />\n| antenna_spire      = {{convert|270|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| floor_count        = 55 (plus 3 underground)\n| floor_area         = {{convert|84000|m2|sqft|-2|abbr=on}}\n| architect          = [[Gerard de Preu and Partners]]<br />[[Perrott Lyon Mathieson]]\n| main_contractor    = [[Grocon|Grollo Australia]]\n}}\n\n'''Rialto''' (often '''The Rialto, or Rialto Towers''') is a [[skyscraper]] located at 525 [[Collins Street, Melbourne|Collins Street]], in the western side of the [[Melbourne central business district|central business district]] of [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]]. It was the tallest [[office]] building in the [[Southern Hemisphere]] when it was constructed.\n\nThe Rialto featured Melbourne's first skyscraper public observation deck which operated between 1994 and 31 December 2009.<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/video/2009/10/23/2722902.htm</ref> It was also the location of Melbourne's first [[Tower running]] event.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Robbs building melbourne.jpg|thumb|left|Robbs Building, demolished in 1980 to make way for the Rialto's concrete and glass podium]]\n[[File:Rialto old.....jpg|thumb|150px|right|The old Rialto Building was retained as part of the development.]]\nThe site of Rialto (Flinders Lane, Collins Street, Winfield Square and Robbs Lane) was occupied by several buildings including numerous small warehouses on Flinders Lane, Robb's Buildings (now demolished, named for the owner, railway builder [[John Robb (civil engineer)|John Robb]]), a grand classical styled 5-storey Victorian office building designed by Thomas Watts and Sons<ref>[http://www.slv.vic.gov.au/miscpics/0/0/9/doc/mp009620.shtml Robb's buildings, corner of Collins and King Streets Melbourne [picture&#93; by<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> in 1885, and one of the largest in the city at the time<ref>[http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A060044b.htm Robb, John (1834\u20131896) Biographical Entry \u2013 Australian Dictionary of Biography Online<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> two other interwar buildings on Collins Street, the Rialto Building (1889) designed by [[William Pitt (architect)|William Pitt]] and the Winfield Building (1890) designed by Charles Debro & Richard Speight, all part of an historic streetscape along Collins Street running up to the Olderfleet Building to the east.\n\nDuring the 1970s, the large derelict site was owned by the [[National Mutual Life Association of Australasia]] and it was around 1979 when the first development proposal was prepared and submitted to the [[Melbourne City Council]].\n\nLittle progress was made until 1980 when the site was acquired by [[Grocon|Grollo Australia]] in a joint venture with St Martin's Properties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rialto.com.au/|title=Building Construction|accessdate=17 January 2007|pages=(Building Profile \u2192 Features \u2192 Construction)}} <!-- due to Javascript navigation used at the site, it is impossible to provide a direct link to the source page --></ref> Though a campaign was run by the National Trust of Victoria against the demolition of Robb's Building, Grocon successfully argued that it stood in the way of its major twin-tower proposal. During the application process the Rialto and Windfield buildings were added to the Victorian Heritage Register, and a different future was determined for them. This involved the creation of a hotel utilising the whole of the long rear wing of the Rialto Building, the replacement of the rear wing of the Winfield Building, and the creation of an atrium between.\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Rialto Towers at night.jpg|thumb|left|Rialto at night.]]\nRobb's buildings were subsequently demolished opening the way for construction to begin on the Rialto.\n\nDesigned by architects Gerard de Preu and Partners in association with [[Perrott Lyon Mathieson]], the building was built between 1982 and 1986, opening in October 1986, and takes its name from the much older Rialto Building next door. The massive glass [[curtain wall (architecture)|curtain wall]] [[fa\u00e7ade]] of reinforced blue tinted mirrored glass is its central feature and changes colour during the day, ranging from a trademark dark blue to a brilliant gold during sunset.\n\nIt is {{convert|251|m|abbr=on}} high, with 55 floors<ref>http://www.rialto.com.au/#block-gp-global-leasing</ref> and 3 basement floors. It comprises two conjoined towers, the shorter North Tower being {{convert|185|m|abbr=on}} high with 43 floors. In total, there are {{convert|84000|m2|abbr=on}} of office space.\n\nEarly tenants moved into the lower floors while the upper floors were still under construction in 1984.\n\n==Rialto Run-up==\nInspired by the popular [[Empire State Building Run-Up]], a stair race up the {{convert|242|m|abbr=on}}, 1222\u20131254 step race to the 53rd floor of the Rialto building was first run in the late 1980s and became an annual event with both men's and women's divisions known as the '''Rialto Run-up'''.  Previous winners include Robin Rishworth (1989,1990); Geoff Case (1991).  The winner was awarded with a trip to [[New York City]] to compete in the Empire State Building race. The event was run until 2005 and competitors had to go up 1254 steps.<ref>Cool Running website [http://www.coolrunning.com.au/mediareleases/2005/rialto.pdf Rialto Run-Up 2005 Run 1254 stairs to the top! ] Retrieved 8 April 2015</ref>\n\n==Observation Deck==\nThe Melbourne Observation Deck opened to the public on 19 July 1994 and was located on the 55th floor of the South Tower, at {{convert|234|m|abbr=on}}. Views of up to {{convert|60|km|abbr=on}} can be had on a clear day. The floor is serviced by two passenger [[Elevator|lift]]s. On 31 December 2009, the observation deck closed. In 2010, the fine dining restaurant, Vue de monde, and associated cocktail bar, Lui Bar, opened for trade on Level 55.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/travel/travel-news/end-in-view-for-rialtos-top-deck-20091007-gn8m.html|title=End in view for Rialto's top deck|last=Dobbin|first=Marika|date=8 October 2009|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=21 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rialto view night.jpg|800px|center|thumb|Panoramic view from the Rialto at night showing the [[Melbourne city centre]] and [[Southbank, Victoria|Southbank]] illuminated]]\n[[File:Melbourne Skyline from Rialto Crop - Nov 2008.jpg|800px|thumb|center|A ~180-degree panoramic image of Melbourne's [[Hoddle Grid]] ([[Melbourne city centre|CBD]]) and [[Southbank, Victoria|Southbank]] on the right side, as viewed from the Rialto Observation Deck]]\n\n{{Clear left}}\n\n==Statistics==\n[[File:Melbourne at night, 2014.jpg|thumb|Rialto dominating Melbourne's western skyline]]\nRialto consists of two interconnected towers, North and South, with rooftop floors at Level 41 and Level 58 respectively. There are 36 passenger lifts, {{convert|95|km|abbr=on}} of lift cables, 706 lift door openings and 1,450 staircase steps.  The outer surface of the building has 13,000 windows. There are five basement levels of car park available for occupiers and casual users. When completed in 1986, The Rialto surpassed Sydney's [[MLC Centre]] to become Australia's tallest building at {{convert|251|m|abbr=on}}. It was the tallest for five years until being surpassed by [[101 Collins Street]] in 1991. It is currently the [[List of tallest buildings in Australia|tenth tallest building in Australia]].\n\n{{Tallest buildings in Australia|taller=[[Bourke Place]]|theight={{convert|254|m}}|shorter=[[Infinity Tower (Brisbane)|Infinity Tower]]|sheight={{convert|249|m}}}}\n\n{{Melbourne tall buildings|taller=[[Bourke Place]]|theight={{convert|254|m}}|shorter=[[Melbourne Central Shopping Centre|Melbourne Central]]|sheight={{convert|246|m}}}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Rialto Tower August 2007.JPG|August 2007\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Architecture}}}}\n* [[Architecture of Melbourne]]\n* [[Australian landmarks]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Melbourne]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.rialto.com.au/ Rialto Towers]\n*[http://www.melbourne360rialto.com.au/ Melbourne Observation Deck]\n*[http://www.walkingmelbourne.com/building280.html Walking Melbourne profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060526194812/http://www.supersprint.com.au/Default.aspx?Menu=269&Content=2839&Template=1 Rialto Run Up]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110218133217/http://www.grollogroup.com.au/grollo-property/development/rialto/ Grollo Group built & owns the Rialto Towers]\n\n{{Melbourne Skyscrapers}}\n{{Melbourne landmarks}}\n\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1986]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Office buildings in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Australia]]\n[[Category:Collins Street, Melbourne]]\n", "name_user": "Ashton 29", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGallery", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rialto_Towers"}
{"title_page": "Homicide statistics by gender", "text_new": "{{see|Sex differences in crime}}\nAccording to the data given by the [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]], worldwide, 78.7% of homicide victims are men, and in 193 of the 202 listed countries or regions, men were more likely to be killed than women. In two, the ratio was 50:50 ([[Switzerland]] and [[British Virgin Islands]]), and in the remaining seven \u2013 [[Tonga]], [[Iceland]], [[Japan]], [[New Zealand]], [[South Korea]], [[Latvia]], and [[Hong Kong]] \u2013 women were slightly more likely to be victims of homicides compared to males.<ref name=\"UNDOC1\"/> A 2013 global study on homicide by the [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] found that men accounted for about 96 percent of all homicide perpetrators worldwide <ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.unodc.org/documents/gsh/pdfs/2014_GLOBAL_HOMICIDE_BOOK_web.pdf|title = Global Study on Homicide|date = 2013|accessdate = |website = www.unodc.org|publisher = United National Office of Drugs and Crime (Vienna)|last = Gibbons|first = Jonathan}}</ref> and 79% of the victims (see the chart below). The homicide rate is per year per 100,000 inhabitants.\n\n{{Rank| rows={{TRC|ignore=4|id=nations}}| header-lines=7| caption=Homicide Victims by Gender, by Country<ref name=UNDOC1>[http://www.unodc.org/gsh/en/data.html UNDOC Homicide Statistics 2013] used tables: [http://www.unodc.org/documents/gsh/data/GSH2013_Homicide_count_and_rate.xlsx Homicide counts and rates] & [http://www.unodc.org/documents/gsh/data/GSH2013_Sex_data.xlsx Percentage of male and female homicide victims] Retrieved May-31-2014</ref>}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable nowrap mw-datatable\" border=1 style=\"text-align:right;\" id=\"nations\"\n|- \n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=3 |<br><br><br><br><br><br>'''Country'''\n! colspan=\"2\" | Total\n! colspan=\"3\" | Male\n! colspan=\"3\" | Female\n! colspan=\"3\" |\n|- valign=bottom\n! scope=\"col\" |'''Homicides'''\n! scope=\"col\" |'''Homicide<br>